According to the logs, dispatch sent
another call ten minutes after the domestic.

127
00:07:36,249 --> 00:07:39,304
Drug activity
at the raymond jennings project

128
00:07:39,304 --> 00:07:41,216
where the tape recorder was found.

129
00:07:41,216 --> 00:07:44,293
If Washington responded to that call,
the timeline adds up.

130
00:07:44,293 --> 00:07:46,934
Raymond jennings wasn't
even in our district.

131
00:07:46,934 --> 00:07:49,820
Why would Joe go there and
not tell no one?

132
00:07:49,820 --> 00:07:51,861
That's what we got to find out.

133
00:07:59,247 --> 00:08:02,974
I did live in the raymond jennings project,
young lady.

134
00:08:02,974 --> 00:08:05,741
And I called the police that night.

135
00:08:05,741 --> 00:08:08,284
My tax pays your salary.

136
00:08:08,284 --> 00:08:11,865
30 years is a long time to remember
a call you made, Ms. Gloria.

137
00:08:11,865 --> 00:08:15,414
I remember real good, sir.
You want to know why?

138
00:08:15,414 --> 00:08:19,729
Because those damn police
actually came for once.

139
00:08:19,729 --> 00:08:21,227
What does that mean?

140
00:08:21,227 --> 00:08:24,036
Black folks from the project calling
on Friday night,

141
00:08:24,036 --> 00:08:25,915
police don't come.

142
00:08:25,915 --> 00:08:28,707
But that night that
black cop showed up.

143
00:08:28,707 --> 00:08:32,392
And he gets to fighting
with the drug dealer.

144
00:08:32,591 --> 00:08:35,185
- What drug dealer?
- Never saw him before,

145
00:08:35,185 --> 00:08:38,455
but after I called the police,
I went out to see what happened,

146
00:08:38,455 --> 00:08:41,610
not expecting a damn thing.

147
00:08:46,420 --> 00:08:47,748
Get off my court.

148
00:08:47,748 --> 00:08:49,064
You don't own this.

149
00:08:49,064 --> 00:08:51,284
Well, I own this. I own you.

150
00:08:51,284 --> 00:08:53,735
I own everything you is, Joe boy.

151
00:08:55,372 --> 00:08:56,677
You ain't better than me.

152
00:08:56,677 --> 00:08:59,131
You just pretend you is.

153
00:09:07,895 --> 00:09:09,823
The dealer called him Joe?

154
00:09:09,823 --> 00:09:12,845
Joe this, Joe that.

155
00:09:12,845 --> 00:09:17,238
That black cop must have come
around the projects regular

156
00:09:17,238 --> 00:09:19,913
'cause he knew enough not
to park at the curb.

157
00:09:19,913 --> 00:09:22,691
Those drug dealers'll see him
a-coming a mile away.

158
00:09:22,691 --> 00:09:24,549
What'd the drug dealer look like?

159
00:09:24,549 --> 00:09:26,327
Skinny.

160
00:09:26,327 --> 00:09:27,617
Young.

161
00:09:27,617 --> 00:09:29,026
Black.

162
00:09:29,026 --> 00:09:32,525
Strutting around like
some sort of crazy rooster.

163
00:09:32,525 --> 00:09:34,838
My eyes been bad since forever.

164
00:09:34,838 --> 00:09:36,390
Can't tell you more.

165
00:09:36,390 --> 00:09:39,786
But I did hear those druggies
calling him "the runner".

166
00:09:39,907 --> 00:09:42,413
- What?
- The runner.

167
00:09:42,413 --> 00:09:45,080
What kinda name is that?

168
00:09:47,090 --> 00:09:49,258
Thank you, Ms. Menards.

169
00:09:50,388 --> 00:09:54,306
Washington called the killer
that on the tape, the runner.

170
00:09:54,306 --> 00:09:56,053
'Cause he knew him.

171
00:09:56,230 --> 00:09:58,011
They both knew each other.

172
00:09:58,011 --> 00:10:00,139
Real well.

173
00:10:03,692 --> 00:10:06,950
I did patrol of the raymond
jennings projects in the '70s.

174
00:10:06,950 --> 00:10:09,179
Never heard the name the runner.

175
00:10:09,179 --> 00:10:12,186
Guy ain't in the system anywhere.
No arrests, nothing.

176
00:10:12,186 --> 00:10:15,224
So how'd this runner and
Washington get so cozy?

177
00:10:15,224 --> 00:10:17,954
And how'd Washington know those projects
enough to know where to park

178
00:10:17,954 --> 00:10:20,079
when he didn't even work that district?

179
00:10:20,079 --> 00:10:22,813
Maybe he had it in for drug dealers.

180
00:10:22,939 --> 00:10:24,665
Washingtong's patrol log.

181
00:10:24,665 --> 00:10:27,912
Radioed in calls on dealers
in his district constantly.

182
00:10:27,912 --> 00:10:29,843
Got into two altercations.

183
00:10:29,843 --> 00:10:31,537
There's a lot of hate here.

184
00:10:31,537 --> 00:10:32,670
Love hate.

185
00:10:32,670 --> 00:10:34,154
No arrests on his record.

186
00:10:34,154 --> 00:10:36,159
Smoke and mirrors?

187
00:10:36,349 --> 00:10:39,717
Acts tough for appearances' sake,
but he's really on the take?

188
00:10:39,717 --> 00:10:41,598
Bank records don't show cash coming in.

189
00:10:41,598 --> 00:10:43,927
But cash was going out,
every few weeks.

190
00:10:43,927 --> 00:10:46,541
These didn't cover
his usual living expenses.

191
00:10:46,541 --> 00:10:49,517
He wrote clearly marked
checks for those.

192
00:10:49,517 --> 00:10:51,831
And these sums are
big enough to stand out.

193
00:10:51,831 --> 00:10:54,356
What are we thinking, buying drugs?

194
00:10:54,356 --> 00:10:58,385
No, addicts clean out bank
within a couple months.

195
00:10:58,385 --> 00:11:00,022
This doesn't follow that pattern.

196
00:11:00,022 --> 00:11:01,985
So what was he doing?

197
00:11:01,985 --> 00:11:04,061
Maybe his widow knows.

198
00:11:04,787 --> 00:11:05,980
The runner?

199
00:11:05,980 --> 00:11:07,397
No.

200
00:11:07,397 --> 00:11:09,339
I never heard of him.

201
00:11:10,244 --> 00:11:13,151
How long were you married, Diane?

202
00:11:13,394 --> 00:11:16,666
Ten months, two weeks.

203
00:11:17,009 --> 00:11:20,243
Was Joe a big spender? Um...

204
00:11:20,243 --> 00:11:22,536
first year of marriage and all.

205
00:11:22,536 --> 00:11:25,488
No. We just got the house.

206
00:11:25,488 --> 00:11:27,009
Why?

207
00:11:27,409 --> 00:11:28,898
Um,

208
00:11:28,898 --> 00:11:33,187
these checks he wrote
for cash every few weeks.

209
00:11:33,187 --> 00:11:36,706
Do you know what they were for?

210
00:11:37,525 --> 00:11:40,404
He got me flowers every Friday.

211
00:11:40,404 --> 00:11:42,981
And movies.

212
00:11:42,981 --> 00:11:45,868
We went to movies all the time.

213
00:11:45,868 --> 00:11:50,447
But I never thought
it would amount to that much.

214
00:11:52,927 --> 00:11:56,303
I thought things would be
different by now.

215
00:11:56,303 --> 00:11:58,829
That I'd be different.

216
00:12:01,411 --> 00:12:05,198
Time makes things worse, not better.

217
00:12:05,399 --> 00:12:08,632
Maybe time also finds the truth.

218
00:12:10,114 --> 00:12:14,850
Can you tell me what you
remember from that day, Diane?

219
00:12:17,932 --> 00:12:21,409
We were thinking about
what to name our baby.

220
00:12:23,124 --> 00:12:25,072
Our little girl.

221
00:12:30,540 --> 00:12:32,478
- Marianne.
- No.

222
00:12:33,586 --> 00:12:35,551
- Martha.
- Uh-uh.

223
00:12:35,714 --> 00:12:37,921
- Matilda.
- No way.

224
00:12:37,921 --> 00:12:39,268
Okay, Mr. Man,

225
00:12:39,268 --> 00:12:42,042
